<ns18:section xmlns:ns18="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.concepts.developmentProcess.openSource.licenses.gnuPublicLicense">

  <ns19:title xmlns:ns19="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Promoting free software via the GNU Public License (GPL)</ns19:title>
  <ns20:para xmlns:ns20="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    The GNU public license was developed by <ns21:emphasis xmlns:ns21="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Richard Stallman</ns21:emphasis> who formed 
    the <ns22:emphasis xmlns:ns22="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Free Software Foundation</ns22:emphasis> for the GNU projects. While
    the BSD license permits unlimited commercial use of the software, and hence also the possibility
    to develop derived commercial products from the open-source software, the GPL is designed to
    prevent the creation of commercial software based on open-source software. It thus explicitly
    promotes the philosophy of free and open-source software. The core features of the GPL are 
    <ns23:orderedlist xmlns:ns23="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      <ns24:listitem xmlns:ns24="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns25:para xmlns:ns25="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        Software licenses under GPL must be freely available. 
      </ns25:para></ns24:listitem>
      <ns26:listitem xmlns:ns26="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns27:para xmlns:ns27="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        The source code for any software licensed via GPL must be made available.
      </ns27:para></ns26:listitem>
      <ns28:listitem xmlns:ns28="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns29:para xmlns:ns29="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        Any software which makes use of software under GPL, must be licensed under GPL.
      </ns29:para></ns28:listitem>
    </ns23:orderedlist>
  </ns20:para>
  
  <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" href="whatDoesGnuMean.docbook"/>
</ns18:section>